Hello,

I've had some problems with the speed of code copying memory (using memcpy sim procedure), it mostly happen when symbolic translates his minimal value to a high value and it causes for a very long step (hours).
I've made a simple code (with binaries):
```
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <string.h>

int main() {
        int* ptr = malloc(0x1000000);
        int* ptr2 = malloc(0x1000000);

        if (ptr != NULL && ptr2 != NULL) {
                memcpy(ptr, ptr2, 0x1000000);
                printf("Copy finished!");
        }
}
```
I've also attached an compiled binaries of this code: both arm and x64 elf files: 
[memcpy_large_size.zip](https://github.com/angr/angr/files/2145252/memcpy_large_size.zip)

Running the x64 executable works very fast running in linux ubuntu (./memcpy_large_size) (just to see real life regular run time).
I am trying to run the arm version using angr and when it reach the memcpy sim procedure it takes hours to copy the memory.

Is this a python problem copying memory? Is there anything I can do to make it work faster since this is just copying memory?

When setting a schema on resources, unresolvable references are not checked upon creation.

When creating a resource that is checked against that schema, a `RefResolutionError` is raised by `jsonschema` and not caught.

For example, creating the schema:

```json
{"data": {
    "schema": {
      "properties": {
        "address": { "$ref": "#/definitions/address" }
      }
    }
  }
}
```

POST data:

```json
{ "data": {
   "address": "seattle"
  }
}
```

This will crash the server with a 500 error and the following message:

```shell
"Unresolvable JSON pointer: %r" % fragment
jsonschema.exceptions.RefResolutionError: Unresolvable JSON pointer: 'definitions/address' 
```

I can work on this, I was just wondering what you all felt the approach should be.

It can either check when creating the schema or upon each invocation of it (i.e., POST data). The only slight trouble I can see with checking and not allowing unresolvable schema is that the schema can be a url, so if it is not resolving at the time of creation, it will fail.

That seems fair to me; does that seem like a reasonable fix?

I would like to add a permission but want to some feedback on the API before I implement.

You would have two options and I'm proposing to add both:

## Option 1: Custom queryset method

This option would let you overwrite how a queryset is filter.

```python
class UserNode(DjangoObjectType):
  class Meta:
    model = User
    interfaces = (relay.Node,)
    only_fields = ('email', 'first_name', 'last_name')

  @classmethod
  def get_queryset (cls, queryset, args, request, info):
    return queryset.filter(owner=request.user)
```

## Option 2: Permissions List

This option would setup a Meta API to use to definte

```python
def auth_required(queryset, args, request, info):
  if request.user.is_authenticated():
    return queryset

  return queryset.none()

class UserNode(DjangoObjectType):
  class Meta:
    model = User
    interfaces = (relay.Node,)
    only_fields = ('email', 'first_name', 'last_name')
    permissions = [auth_required]
```

If these look like good APIs then I'll implement.

@nibanks brought to my attention that currently the MTU in OpenThread is being set to 1500 bytes. 

This value should be changed to 1280 bytes. Smaller packets means better performance. Using the minimum MTU ensures that we keep the amount of layer-2 fragmentation to a minimum. 

A busy TCP stream over a Thread network will perform worse with a 1500 MTU than a 1280 MTU.

Within cli.cpp the ProcessScan method creates a uint16_t to store the bitmap for scanning channels, this limits channels upto 15, it should be changed to a uint32_t to accomidate for the full 27 channels in the IEEE spec :)

`void Interpreter::ProcessScan(int argc, char *argv[])
{
    ThreadError error = kThreadError_None;
    uint16_t scanChannels = 0;
    long value;

    if (argc > 0)
    {
        SuccessOrExit(error = ParseLong(argv[0], value));
        scanChannels = 1 << value;
    }

    SuccessOrExit(error = otActiveScan(scanChannels, 0, &HandleActiveScanResult));
    sServer->OutputFormat("| J | Network Name     | Extended PAN     | PAN  | MAC Address      | Ch | dBm | LQI |\r\n");
    sServer->OutputFormat("+---+------------------+------------------+------+------------------+----+-----+-----+\r\n");

    return;

exit:
    AppendResult(error);
}`

to 

`void Interpreter::ProcessScan(int argc, char *argv[])
{
    ThreadError error = kThreadError_None;
    uint32_t scanChannels = 0;
    long value;

    if (argc > 0)
    {
        SuccessOrExit(error = ParseLong(argv[0], value));
        scanChannels = 1 << value;
    }

    SuccessOrExit(error = otActiveScan(scanChannels, 0, &HandleActiveScanResult));
    sServer->OutputFormat("| J | Network Name     | Extended PAN     | PAN  | MAC Address      | Ch | dBm | LQI |\r\n");
    sServer->OutputFormat("+---+------------------+------------------+------+------------------+----+-----+-----+\r\n");

    return;

exit:
    AppendResult(error);
}`

I am trying to implement Python bindings for a C++ library and like how pybind11 makes life easier. Thanks for that!

But I ran into a few issues regarding threads. Let me try to explain. The library records audio signals and lets clients handle the samples through a callback. The way the callback mechanism is implemented is to attach a Listener to a Controller. When new samples arrive, the Controller informs the (Python) listener by calling a virtual method (let's call it `doit`) to handle the data.

Since the library works with threads, I followed the instructions regarding locking the GIL. But if I call  pybind11::gil_scoped_acquire, it locks the application. I'm not sure if this is an error or my mistake (probably the latter ;) ). But I hope someone can help me to point me in the right direction, because it got my stuck for two days now. 

I made a clean example to demonstrate the locking. I simulate an event either by calling  `call_doit` or `call_doit_thread` from Python. `call_doit` will properly call the overloaded method `doit`. It runs on the same thread as Python. When using `call_doit_thread` the module tries to call the overloaded method from a std::thread. Then the module locks at `pybind11::gil_scoped_acquire gil;` (an expression inside the macro PYBIND11_OVERLOAD_PURE).

```cpp
#include <pybind11/pybind11.h>
namespace py = pybind11;

#include <string>
#include <thread>
#include <iostream>

namespace Sandbox {

class ListenerBase
{
public:
	virtual ~ListenerBase() {}
	virtual void doit(std::string caller) = 0;
};

class Controller
{
public:
	Controller(ListenerBase& base) : _base(base) {}
	void call_doit() { internal_call_doit("call_doit"); }
	void call_doit_thread()
	{
		std::thread t([this]() mutable { internal_call_doit("call_doit_thread"); });
		t.join();
	}
private:
	ListenerBase& _base;
	void internal_call_doit(std::string calledFrom)
	{
		{
			std::cout << calledFrom << "[just before calling]" << std::endl;
			_base.doit(calledFrom);
			std::cout << calledFrom << "[just after calling]" << std::endl;
		}
	}
};

class PyListenerBase : public ListenerBase
{
public:
	/* Inherit the constructors */
	using ListenerBase::ListenerBase;

	/* Trampoline (need one for each virtual function) */
	void doit(std::string caller)
	{
		//		PYBIND11_OVERLOAD_PURE(
		//				void,           /* Return type */
		//				ListenerBase,   /* Parent class */
		//				doit,           /* Name of function */
		//				caller          /* Argument(s) */
		//		);
		// Expands to:

	     pybind11::gil_scoped_acquire gil;
	     pybind11::function overload = pybind11::get_overload(this, "doit");
	     if (overload)
	    	 return overload.call(caller).template cast<void>();
	    pybind11::pybind11_fail("Tried to call pure virtual function \"doit\"");
	}
};

PYBIND11_PLUGIN(Sandbox)
{
	py::init_threading();

	py::module sandbox("Sandbox","Sandbox suite");

	py::class_<Controller>(sandbox,"Controller")
		.def(py::init<ListenerBase&>())
		.def("call_doit", &Controller::call_doit)
		.def("call_doit_thread", &Controller::call_doit_thread)
		;

	py::class_<PyListenerBase>(sandbox,"ListenerBase")
	   .alias<ListenerBase>()
	   .def(py::init<>())
	   .def("doit", &ListenerBase::doit)
	   ;

	return sandbox.ptr();
}

} /* namespace Sandbox */
```

In Python I can use the module as:
```python
import Sandbox
sb = Sandbox;

class MyPythonListener(sb.ListenerBase):
    def doit(self,caller):
        print 'MyPythonListener called by {0}'.format(caller);

listener = MyPythonListener();
controller = sb.Controller(listener);

print 'calling doit' 
controller.call_doit()

print 'calling doit on thread'
controller.call_doit_thread()
```

which results in:
```
>>> calling doit
>>> call_doit[just before calling]
>>> MyPythonListener called by call_doit
>>> call_doit[just after calling]
>>> calling doit on thread
>>> call_doit_thread[just before calling]
```

I accidentally used the same name twice which lead to hard-to-debug segfaults that only happened when the class got imported twice or some other python module was loaded. 

Therefore I think it might be nice to do a compile-time or runtime check if the name was already registered.

I added this little function

```
for (auto other_info : internals.registered_types_py) {
     std::string other = ((const detail::type_info *) (other_info.second))->type->tp_name;
     if (strcmp(other.c_str(), full_name.c_str()) == 0) {
          pybind11_fail(full_name + " registered previously!");
      }
 }
```
to the `initialize (type_record *rec)` code to do a check on import if there are duplicates already.

Util function sanitize_url [from here](https://github.com/python-social-auth/social-core/blob/master/social_core/utils.py#L86) is vulnerable to open redirect attack if redirect_to is something like **'////evil.com'**. In this case `urlparse(redirect_to)[1]` equals to `''`, `netloc` is set to `hosts[0]` and value of redirect_to is returned.

```python  
def sanitize_redirect(hosts, redirect_to):
    if redirect_to:
        try:
            # if redirect_to is '////evil.com', urlparse(...)[1] is ''  
            netloc = urlparse(redirect_to)[1] or hosts[0]  # so we set netloc = hosts[0]
        except (TypeError, AttributeError):
            pass
        else:
            if netloc in hosts:  # yes, netloc in hosts
                return redirect_to  # returning '////evil.com' 
```

